there's limited time today

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:53.590
to go into all the
mechanics of the games,

00:10:53.590 --> 00:10:57.640
but just for those of you who
are looking at what's working,

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:02.135
we think that Goodgame
is a really good example.

00:11:02.135 --> 00:11:04.260
So a slightly different
demographic with Pixelberry

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:05.460
here.

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:06.070
I pick Truth!

00:11:06.070 --> 00:11:06.620
I pick Dare!

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:08.230
I pick just making out!

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:10.810
So I don't know if this is
everybody's game in the place,

00:11:10.810 --> 00:11:13.180
but they've done
some amazing things.

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:16.130
They just started in
the middle of 2012

00:11:16.130 --> 00:11:18.780
and just launched on Play
just a few months ago.

00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:21.080
But one thing that's really
interesting about them

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:24.380
and really differentiated
is passion about story

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:26.540
and not just saying
that, but if you

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:28.360
look at the employees
of the company,

00:11:28.360 --> 00:11:30.590
a full half of the
people at Pixelberry

00:11:30.590 --> 00:11:32.540
are actually writers.

00:11:32.540 --> 00:11:34.260
And so when you
think about that,

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:36.519
that's just a huge
commitment to doing that,

00:11:36.519 --> 00:11:38.560
and then you look at the
day one retention number

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:40.280
and clearly it's
paying off for them.

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:44.670
I mean 71% is massive,
and so these guys, they've

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:47.680
taken a very story-driven
approach to the business,

00:11:47.680 --> 00:11:50.480
and it's working for them.

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:53.440
And one thing too is just
on the bottom left there,

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:55.390
cyberbullying is
something where,

00:11:55.390 --> 00:11:57.500
I spoke to Oliver, the
founder and he was saying,

00:11:57.500 --> 00:12:00.520
I wanted to know how he got into
cyberbullying because they're

00:12:00.520 --> 00:12:02.840
doing some really cool
things with Cybersmile, which

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:05.114
is a cyberbullying charity.

00:12:05.114 --> 00:12:06.780
And he said we had
started the game when

00:12:06.780 --> 00:12:09.620
we were doing this thing and
he was reading more and more

00:12:09.620 --> 00:12:10.540
about cyberbullying.

00:12:10.540 --> 00:12:13.110
And he said, we have
this amazing platform

00:12:13.110 --> 00:12:15.270
with "High School Story"
to do something about it.

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:17.020
And so it's actually
really cool that they

00:12:17.020 --> 00:12:20.120
have Cybersmile-inspired
quests, and they've

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:23.390
had more than two million
people go through them.

00:12:23.390 --> 00:12:28.450
And they also have a bunch
of different donations

00:12:28.450 --> 00:12:32.780
as well as they've actually
had people who-- cyberbullying

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:35.950
or even suicidal situations
to be able to help.

00:12:35.950 --> 00:12:38.630
So for here, they're
building a business,

00:12:38.630 --> 00:12:41.400
but it's really inspiring
for us that we're

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:45.620
seeing them do so
much good as well.

00:12:45.620 --> 00:12:48.990
And then Space
Ape, new developer

00:12:48.990 --> 00:12:52.110
launched "Samurai Siege" in the
fourth quarter of last year.

00:12:52.110 --> 00:12:55.380
Recently formed as well,
just a really talented team.

00:12:55.380 --> 00:12:57.280
So these guys really
stand out so a bunch

00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:00.940
of ex-Playfish and Mind
Candy folks based in London.

00:13:00.940 --> 00:13:04.010
And so they're just really smart
and really analytical about how

00:13:04.010 --> 00:13:07.105
they run their business, and
that's been quite fun to see.

00:13:07.105 --> 00:13:08.480
And so that for
them, it was just

00:13:08.480 --> 00:13:10.104
how they thought
about their first game

00:13:10.104 --> 00:13:12.140
was just get it
out there, be fast.

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:13.220
They have more on the
pipeline that they're

00:13:13.220 --> 00:13:14.500
really excited
about as well too.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:16.140
But you can look at
the headline here,

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:20.760
and "Events" is a well-known
structure for just improving

00:13:20.760 --> 00:13:22.460
a variety of metrics
within your game.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:24.990
There's definitely a
fair amount of investment

00:13:24.990 --> 00:13:29.560
that's required to do that, but
it can work for a lot of folks.

00:13:29.560 --> 00:13:32.630
And so "Events" are an area
where Space Ape has really

00:13:32.630 --> 00:13:35.615
chosen to invest and to try
to differentiate itself,

00:13:35.615 --> 00:13:37.740
and so they have a variety
of different tournaments

00:13:37.740 --> 00:13:40.260
that we lay out here, and you
can look at the relative impact

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:40.760
there.

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:43.280
And so the top one is what they
call a personal tournament,

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:45.980
or how they describe is it's
March Madness right now,

00:13:45.980 --> 00:13:49.610
so kind of an enunciated bracket
for events within the game

00:13:49.610 --> 00:13:53.660
where it's single player, so
not having to join an alliance,

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:56.120
multiround, and at
the end of that,

00:13:56.120 --> 00:13:58.230
you have one single
winner through

00:13:58.230 --> 00:13:59.880
that personal tournament.

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:01.870
In the second one we
have the "War Rush,"

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:05.830
so that's just a compression of
the existing "Alliance Wars,"

00:14:05.830 --> 00:14:08.360
but rather than 12 hours, you
move it down to three hours,

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:10.400
and you get a lot of
good things in terms

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.594
of just the engagement in
the game during that time,

00:14:12.594 --> 00:14:14.010
but as you can
imagine, that might

00:14:14.010 --> 00:14:15.301
be a little tiring as well too.

00:14:15.301 --> 00:14:18.580
So they're iterating on a bunch
of different event structures,

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:20.920
and as you can see
here, they're measuring,

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:23.700
what was the effort level
required to support that?

00:14:23.700 --> 00:14:26.427
What did it do to our metrics
in terms of retention engagement

00:14:26.427 --> 00:14:27.010
modernization?

00:14:30.150 --> 00:14:31.950
And then onto the small
developer category.

00:14:31.950 --> 00:14:34.420
So as I mentioned
earlier, some really

00:14:34.420 --> 00:14:37.660
stand-out folks with Vector
Unit and with Mediocre,

00:14:37.660 --> 00:14:40.570
where it's largely for
both of these companies,

00:14:40.570 --> 00:14:43.710
about two people, which
is really quite amazing.

00:14:43.710 --> 00:14:46.030
And the point here
is that there's

00:14:46.030 --> 00:14:48.940
a bunch of rules where for the
large developers, if you're

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:52.670
looking to raise money,
build a business,

00:14:52.670 --> 00:14:54.760
you have kind of a
different set of things,

00:14:54.760 --> 00:14:56.800
and I think for the
large developers,

00:14:56.800 --> 00:14:59.480
it's more important to follow
best practices where it can

00:14:59.480 --> 00:15:02.070
be-- you're a bit
more constrained.

00:15:02.070 --> 00:15:05.270
With these guys, if you have a
cost structure of two people,

00:15:05.270 --> 00:15:07.140
you can kind of do
whatever you want,

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:09.910
and these guys are showing that.

00:15:09.910 --> 00:15:13.270
So for Vector Unit with "Riptide
GP2," their state of premium

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:16.967
game and [INAUDIBLE]
is two people

00:15:16.967 --> 00:15:18.300
have done a great job with that.

00:15:18.300 --> 00:15:20.750
As I mentioned earlier,
so no paid advertising,

00:15:20.750 --> 00:15:24.172
so that they do an amazing job
engaging with our community,

00:15:24.172 --> 00:15:25.880
so they were doing a
lot of work in terms

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:29.620
of getting early APKs out
to developers and reviewers,

00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:33.080
doing a bunch of social media,
doing a bunch of cross-promo

00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:35.670
in several of their existing
games, and for them,

00:15:35.670 --> 00:15:38.980
just taking a very sort
of throwback approach

00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:42.010
and just not doing
pay-use acquisition.

00:15:42.010 --> 00:15:44.140
For them too, they work
very closely with us

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:46.700
where they actually
were part of our keynote

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:49.636
last year at Google I/O
Show, where we presented some

00:15:49.636 --> 00:15:51.630
of the multiplayer earlier,
they were basically

00:15:51.630 --> 00:15:52.810
the reference game for that.

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:55.440
So I mean, these guys are
super easy to work with,

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:57.090
and one demonstration
of that is like,

00:15:57.090 --> 00:16:00.160
hey, you guys mind if I'm going
to talk about you guys at GDC,

00:16:00.160 --> 00:16:01.380
and they're like, yeah, sure.

00:16:01.380 --> 00:16:02.879
Here's all our
revenue for the game.

00:16:02.879 --> 00:16:04.697
And so these guys
are like super open.

00:16:04.697 --> 00:16:06.780
You can't quite do this
with like the bigger guys,

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:09.590
but this is what the game did.

00:16:09.590 --> 00:16:12.000
So this is their
Google Play revenue,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.530
and so here you can see when you
have that premium style though,

00:16:16.530 --> 00:16:19.170
you are going to spike
early, and even though they

00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:22.480
do have enough
purchase in the game,

00:16:22.480 --> 00:16:24.540
it does taper off after
that initial purchase

00:16:24.540 --> 00:16:25.320
cycle is through.

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:27.653
But for them, they're driving
a quarter of their revenue

00:16:27.653 --> 00:16:29.400
through in-app
purchases of the game.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:33.700
And for them the message
here is, this is a success.

00:16:33.700 --> 00:16:36.310
it's clearly a success
for Vector Unit.

00:16:36.310 --> 00:16:39.720
If you're a larger company, this
is a more challenging thing,

00:16:39.720 --> 00:16:42.230
but for smaller developers,
it's really important

00:16:42.230 --> 00:16:44.100
that we have diversity
in the ecosystem

00:16:44.100 --> 00:16:45.840
and you have developers
that are making

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:48.555
amazing games of
this quality, and you

00:16:48.555 --> 00:16:50.180
can have a different
product out there.

00:16:50.180 --> 00:16:53.130
There's a bunch of premium
gamers still on Google Play

00:16:53.130 --> 00:16:55.270
even though the in-app
purchase is the dominant way

00:16:55.270 --> 00:16:57.909
that revenue is
generated, so these guys

00:16:57.909 --> 00:16:59.450
are a great example
of somebody who's

00:16:59.450 --> 00:17:02.870
having success doing that.

00:17:02.870 --> 00:17:07.369
Then more recently, some
guys at Mediocre based out

00:17:07.369 --> 00:17:10.530
of Sweden who I've known for
the last several years, so

00:17:10.530 --> 00:17:12.030
interesting game
with "Smash Hit."

00:17:12.030 --> 00:17:14.759
It's blown up right now if
you guys haven't seen it.

00:17:14.759 --> 00:17:15.740
It launched In the
last couple of weeks,

00:17:15.740 --> 00:17:17.156
but they have an
interesting model

00:17:17.156 --> 00:17:19.770
where it's free
with level unlocks.

00:17:19.770 --> 00:17:22.790
So it's pretty basic
modernization in some ways,

00:17:22.790 --> 00:17:24.950
but it's not
something where you're

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:27.826
going to have players pay
you over and over again.

00:17:27.826 --> 00:17:29.200
I asked these guys
the other day,

00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:32.340
I said, is it possible for
me to pay you more than $2

00:17:32.340 --> 00:17:33.530
for this game?

00:17:33.530 --> 00:17:34.544
And they said no.

00:17:34.544 --> 00:17:35.960
And so there's a
lot of developers

00:17:35.960 --> 00:17:39.494
that aren't willing to make that
trade-off, but these guys have.

00:17:39.494 --> 00:17:40.910
And so some of the
changes they've

00:17:40.910 --> 00:17:43.770
made from their previous games,
so the example of "Sprinkle."

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:47.020
Previously, they had separate
APKs for a free and a premium

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:49.490
game, but it's a bit of
an awkward experience.

00:17:49.490 --> 00:17:51.420
And so in this case,
for "Smash Hit,"

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:53.650
they've actually condensed
that into a single APK.

00:17:53.650 --> 00:17:56.750
And so it starts free and then
you have a premium unlock,

00:17:56.750 --> 00:17:59.147
which is a really
nice way to do things.

00:17:59.147 --> 00:18:01.230
And there in terms of the
approach that they take,

00:18:01.230 --> 00:18:03.530
so just really
highly-polished games.

00:18:03.530 --> 00:18:05.160
So getting folks,
it doesn't hurt

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:06.660
that I'm talking
about it now, but I

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:08.660
think they have a lot of
just folks who are just

00:18:08.660 --> 00:18:10.170
passing the game
to their friends,

00:18:10.170 --> 00:18:12.830
showing it to their
friends, really focusing on

00:18:12.830 --> 00:18:16.230
that sort of word-of-mouth
is their approach to getting

00:18:16.230 --> 00:18:17.350
the word out.

00:18:17.350 --> 00:18:20.450
And again, too, they have other
games they can cross-promo.

00:18:20.450 --> 00:18:22.920
They did some PR,
but again, no ads,

00:18:22.920 --> 00:18:27.010
so it is possible
to go that route.

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:30.770
In terms of monetization
results, as I mentioned,

00:18:30.770 --> 00:18:34.430
the game has-- it's a free
game with a premium unlock.

00:18:34.430 --> 00:18:36.780
And so there, you play
through and they say,

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:38.450
hey, you have
these check points.

00:18:38.450 --> 00:18:40.487
It's basically a way
to save your progress

00:18:40.487 --> 00:18:42.070
across the various
levels of the game,

00:18:42.070 --> 00:18:45.176
and so you play through rather
than having to start over

00:18:45.176 --> 00:18:46.550
all the way at
the beginning, you

00:18:46.550 --> 00:18:48.440
can save your progress at a
bunch of intermediate points.

00:18:48.440 --> 00:18:51.450
There is really clear user value
that's created in doing that.

00:18:51.450 --> 00:18:55.240
It's relatively simple, but
it's also very effective.

00:18:55.240 --> 00:18:57.940
In terms of the early results,
that's kind of remarkable.

00:18:57.940 --> 00:18:59.040
It's under two weeks.

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:01.430
I've just been
refreshing my phone,

00:19:01.430 --> 00:19:04.140
but they actually hit number
one on Top Free on Google Play

00:19:04.140 --> 00:19:05.310
yesterday.

00:19:05.310 --> 00:19:07.380
It's pretty amazing that
two guys can do that.

00:19:07.380 --> 00:19:10.140
And as I said, the
monetization is basic,

00:19:10.140 --> 00:19:12.610
and I don't know if it will
exactly follow the "Riptide

00:19:12.610 --> 00:19:15.024
GP2" curve, but these
guys will likely

00:19:15.024 --> 00:19:16.690
spike early in terms
of the monetization

00:19:16.690 --> 00:19:19.330
just because folks like
myself, as much as I would like

00:19:19.330 --> 00:19:23.440
to pay them more than $2 for
the game, I can't, right?

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:26.400
But they have hit Top 100,
top grossing right now too,

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:29.680
so I mean, they are making
good money on the game.

00:19:29.680 --> 00:19:32.880
So that was a quick recap
of a lot of the developers

00:19:32.880 --> 00:19:35.000
that we think are doing
really exceptional things

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.500
for their businesses,
for Google Play,

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:39.340
and should be role
models for a lot

00:19:39.340 --> 00:19:40.783
of the folks in the ecosystem.

00:19:40.783 --> 00:19:42.715
So just a quick
update on our side

00:19:42.715 --> 00:19:44.340
in terms of some of
the things we hear.

00:19:44.340 --> 00:19:47.190
So I mean, I know all you
guys talk to each other,

00:19:47.190 --> 00:19:49.557
but in terms of like
there are some themes

00:19:49.557 --> 00:19:52.140
I just wanted to share with you
guys in terms of what we hear.

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:55.532
And so some of the developers
will come to us and say,

00:19:55.532 --> 00:19:56.490
here's all our metrics.

00:19:56.490 --> 00:19:58.907
Here's Google Play where I
think you guys could do better.

00:19:58.907 --> 00:20:00.406
And so I don't know
if you guys have

00:20:00.406 --> 00:20:02.110
a sense of what
do developers say

00:20:02.110 --> 00:20:04.330
we need to work
on at Google Play?

00:20:04.330 --> 00:20:05.038
Do you guys know?

00:20:07.770 --> 00:20:09.450
So the answer is conversion.

00:20:09.450 --> 00:20:12.500
So it's one of the things
we hear most often where

00:20:12.500 --> 00:20:15.000
we have great
engagement, like we have

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:16.740
a ton of engagement
on Google Play.

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:18.987
Like the payers who
were done, like they're

00:20:18.987 --> 00:20:20.570
spending a bunch of
money on the game,

00:20:20.570 --> 00:20:23.260
but it's the conversion
piece where we would really

00:20:23.260 --> 00:20:25.330
like to see you
guys, Google, work

00:20:25.330 --> 00:20:28.980
on helping us convert more
of our players into payers.

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:31.150
And so that's something
where we hear that,

00:20:31.150 --> 00:20:32.840
and so how do we want to do it?

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:33.340
Right?

00:20:33.340 --> 00:20:36.097
So we've had [INAUDIBLE]
billing programs that

00:20:36.097 --> 00:20:38.612
have been in place
for a number of years.

00:20:38.612 --> 00:20:40.695
Gift cards have started
to roll out more recently,

00:20:40.695 --> 00:20:42.400
but are really
catching momentum,

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:44.440
and we're expending
that more broadly.

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:45.860
Supporting other
forms of payment.

00:20:45.860 --> 00:20:49.450
We're exploring a variety
of different options

00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:51.040
and even for credit card, too.

00:20:51.040 --> 00:20:52.990
One of things we're
focused on is just

00:20:52.990 --> 00:20:55.680
enabling more and more
people to be payment

00:20:55.680 --> 00:20:58.140
ready to have their credit
card on file with Google

00:20:58.140 --> 00:20:59.930
and with Google Play.

00:20:59.930 --> 00:21:01.544
And so how are we
planning to do this?

00:21:01.544 --> 00:21:03.960
And of course, the answer to
this one is all of the above.

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:07.890
And so, we're pursuing all
of these things in parallel.

00:21:07.890 --> 00:21:10.080
And so payments is one of
the big things for us too,

00:21:10.080 --> 00:21:11.810
so all the great
work the developers

00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:15.250
are doing to make
money on the platform.

00:21:15.250 --> 00:21:18.250
A big focus for us right now,
in some ways it's not sexy,

00:21:18.250 --> 00:21:22.042
but it's really important, where
if you have that player who

00:21:22.042 --> 00:21:23.750
has found your game,
installed your game,

00:21:23.750 --> 00:21:26.220
is playing your game, loves
your game, wants to pay for it

00:21:26.220 --> 00:21:28.830
and just gets caught at that
part of the process, that

00:21:28.830 --> 00:21:30.420
really just feels
like it's something

00:21:30.420 --> 00:21:31.230
that shouldn't happen.

00:21:31.230 --> 00:21:32.080
And so it's something
we're spending

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:34.000
a lot of time
focusing on ourselves.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:36.620
